// @run
// @log zero
// @log one
// @log two
// @log three
// CONTRACT (must-not-error): an exhaustive `==`-chain over a FOUR-member numeric
// literal union produces the right label for every value. Extends
// literal-union-exhaustive-elseif.vl (3 members) to confirm the algebra scales
// to four members and both the `if` and `else if` arms are reached.
// Note: uses `==` for literal discrimination. The `is` form for literal types is
// currently broken (always takes else — see docs/soundness-findings.md,
// literal-is-always-false); using `==` is the correct idiom.
function name(n: 0 | 1 | 2 | 3): string {
  if n == 0 { return "zero" }
  else if n == 1 { return "one" }
  else if n == 2 { return "two" }
  else { return "three" }
}
print(name(0))  // zero
print(name(1))  // one
print(name(2))  // two
print(name(3))  // three
